Hyeopjae Beach.adr_address: 329-10 Hallim-ro, Hallim-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do 63011, South Korea

editorial_summary.overview: Tranquil stretch of white sand known for its clear, turquoise water & views of Biyangdo Island.

Hyeopjae Beach.formatted_address: 329-10 Hallim-ro, Hallim-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do, South Korea
Hyeopjae Beach.name: Hyeopjae Beach

reviews.text:
Please note that I live in Costa Rica and am blessed with amazing reefs steps from my house, when I say I was disappointed with the snoring here BUT I loved the rest of it. Snorkeling equipment, super cheap to rent as was the umbrella - all day for about $20 with a mat over the sand to lay on. Plenty of lunch eateries in the area if you don't feel like packing a picnic.
The best part is the water! Very clear! Can easily see yourself while swimming, but it's a small beach and can get a little crowded. There were some surf classes that would at times bump into swimmers.

One of the most popular and beautiful beaches in Jeju Island, known for its white sand, clear turquoise waters, and stunning views of Biyangdo Island in the distance.

The beach is located on the western side of the island, near Hallim Park, making it easy to combine a beach day with a visit to nearby attractions.

Before going to Hyeopjae Beach, it's helpful to know the following:

- The beach is shallow and calm, making it ideal for families with children or those looking for a relaxing swim. It’s also good for wading and playing in the water.
- The sand is soft and perfect for beach walks, while the surrounding volcanic rocks add to the scenic beauty of the area.
- There are convenient facilities like showers, restrooms, and changing rooms, along with nearby cafes and restaurants offering local Jeju food and refreshments.
- During peak season (summer months), the beach can get quite busy, so arriving early is recommended to secure a good spot.
- The sunsets at Hyeopjae Beach are especially beautiful, making it a great spot to relax in the evening.
- It’s also possible to rent beach gear like umbrellas and chairs during the warmer months.
- The area is easily accessible by public transportation or car, with parking available near the beach.

Hyeopjae Beach is a great spot for those looking to enjoy Jeju’s natural beauty, whether for swimming, sunbathing, or just taking in the coastal views.
Very nice and clean beach, in the nearby areas there are many places to eat or buy some souvenirs. The sand is breathtaking, I totally recommended this place

The most popular beach in Aewol for a simple reason. They ALLOW swimming in a small 400m stretch of beach patrolled by lifeguards. All other beaches prohibit swimming and are enforced by life guards on duty.

Parking is scarce and bathrooms are available next to Starbucks.

The area is packed with families so expect a crowded dip if you must. Water is also choppy and the experience not ideal.

Tip :

Toilets are free to the far end of the beach to the west and the nearby shower rooms are chargeable. Rates are attached.

I had a good time here. White sand, cool breeze, View is beautifull while watching sunset at the beach. Strolling around the area is a good idea. There are Many cafes, restaurant and supermarket arround. And there is a cute souvenir shop nearby. Also olive young is also there 🤭

Mysterious Road.adr_address: 2894-63 1100-ro, 노형동 Cheju, Jeju-do 63079, South Korea

editorial_summary.overview: Offbeat attraction with the optical illusion of a downward-sloping hill that looks like an incline.

Mysterious Road.name: Mysterious Road

reviews.text:
This is a short segment of road (about 50 to 80 m long, with signs indicating start and end) which appears to go uphill (optical illusion). Hence, a rolling can or car in neutral gear will seem to "roll uphill".

Several cars stopped on the road, switched on hazard lights, and then either rolled forward/backward up the hill. One has to be very careful as there is traffic on the road.

Took us a few rounds to test out the mysterious road phenomenon. There are signs on both sides of the road saying the Mysterious road starts here. It is not a very long stretch and one could try out this optic illusion using a bottled water or turning off the engine of the car at neutral gear to see the car/bottle going upwards on the uphill slope. Pretty cool.
Highly recommend the Mystic Cafe which has really good pumpkin cake and lovely views.

Supposed to bring a bottle to try out if the bottle can indeed roll uphill, but the water bottles we had were all bigger at the bottom and just roll back and around.
We did try driving with neutral gear and low speed past the start-end stretch, it went quite fast!
But frankly speaking, when we stand there, we couldn't really tell if it was really uphill visually. Seems pretty even both side ... Anyway it was fun watching people trying - they turn on hazard lights at that stretch.

Mysterious Road in Jeju, explored in February, was a fascinating encounter with an optical illusion of nature. Despite its seemingly ordinary appearance, this sloping road challenged the laws of gravity, creating an intriguing and mystifying experience. The illusion of objects rolling uphill defied logic, giving rise to a sense of wonder and curiosity. Even in the winter chill, witnessing this peculiar phenomenon was a highlight, leaving me in awe of the mysteries of nature. The simplicity of the location, coupled with its inexplicable quirk, made Mysterious Road an entertaining and thought-provoking stop during my visit to Jeju.

Went this place without much expectation, because of other locations in jeju made more disappointing. But this place is truly amazing. Felt the illusion. But be very careful while driving. Couldn't believe my eyes. Much excited. Wanted to see again and cross check, so return the way. Return also felt same illusion. Simply awesome. Don't try get distracted while driving and watching the illusion,  by taking photos. While look, road is down/up, but actual its opposite to our view. Simply awesome. Better try this in slower speed and alone in road without other vehicles. Nice experience.

Yongduam Rock.adr_address: 15 Yongduam-gil, 용담2동 Cheju, Jeju-do, South Korea

editorial_summary.overview: Popular oceanfront volcanic rock formation in the shape of a dragon's head.

Yongduam Rock.formatted_address: 15 Yongduam-gil, 용담2동 Cheju, Jeju-do, South Korea
Yongduam Rock.name: Yongduam Rock

reviews.text: Cool quick stop for pictures or souvenirs, if you're lucky you can catch some of the locals serving up straight-from-the-sea seafood right by the rock. I didn't get a chance to partake but it looked like fun!

It’s a very quick sight, and you can park at the nearby area and walk a short distance to the steps to see the rock formation, which resembles a dragon looking out at the sea. On the side we saw some haenyeo equipment (nets) but I think they were hard at work so we didn’t get to see them surface from the water.
A nice spot viewing the sea and the rare shape of rocks along the beach. A few stairways as the accesses to the bottom for a closer look.
Seriously, I couldn't recognize that as a dragon's head from the angle I was standing. You probably can spend 10 minutes to have a look.

Our first tourist spot after arriving in Jeju. Its fine for what it is. Nothing extra special. A decent view of the sea, the small cliffs and the Ramada hotel on the North corner. Those carrying really high def cameras can catch the landing trajectory of airplanes over the sea every 2 mins. There is decent amount of parking space, and it's payable beyond a certain time period. We were waved by without any charges probably we spent like 30 mins there.

Jejumok Gwana Government Office.adr_address: 13 Gwandeok-ro 7-gil, Cheju, Jeju-do 63166, South Korea

editorial_summary.overview: Administrative center dating to the 14th century, reconstructed with reference to original plans.

Jejumok Gwana Government Office.name: Jejumok Gwana Government Office

reviews.text: This is the symbol of ruling Jekumok during the Jonseon Dynasty but also an important site of the history of Jeju.  The place was used as a complex of major administrative buildings since Tamna Kingdom era. The original facilities were destroyed and demolished during the Japanese colonial period. Since 1991, they have made 4 excavation projects and the buildings reconstructed in 2002 and 2006. Nowadays, it shows how communication between people and government worked centuries ago. It is quite common to see local people traditionally dressed taking pictures at the place. The entrance is very cheap, less than 2 dollars. Very important while visiting to take your shoes off before entering the pavilions.
A very interesting place to visit in the old city of Jeju. Stunning athmosphere there.
Great building lots of history here. You can dress up as an emperor for photos. Cost £1.80 for two of us.

Authentic Joseon era buildings and attire.

Tourists rent Hanbok from nearby stores.

A small historical place where you can learn about how ancient governors  lives and govern Jeju Island. There is a volunteer in a building at the rear of the compound who will share with you interesting facts about Jeju during ancient times. The gentleman can speak a bit of English but there are English translation written on the exhibits. Overall an interesting place for a short visit just to learn a bit more about Jeju Island during ancient times.

Spirited Garden.adr_address: 675 Nokchabunjae-ro, Hangyeong-myeon, 특별자치도, Cheju, Jeju-do 63005, South Korea

editorial_summary.overview: With 7 small gardens & native bonsai, this picturesque spot also features a 3-story cafe.

Spirited Garden.formatted_address: 675 Nokchabunjae-ro, Hangyeong-myeon, 특별자치도, Cheju, Jeju-do, South Korea
Spirited Garden.name: Spirited Garden

reviews.text: Wonderful place, it's something one of a kind. It was a highlight in our trip! The food at the restaurant it was really tasty, serving for 2 it's actually for 3 or 4. The personnel was so nice and helpfu🥰l, they even washed our shirt when it got some sauce on it. A big thumbs 👍 !

This garden is truly the work of a lifetime. I can’t begin to explain the thought and care we have witnessed in the way these amazing species are displayed. A truly beautiful and calm moment spent in this garden.

We went on a very cold and rainy day, I can’t imagine how beautiful in must be when it’s sunny.

We also had the privilege of meeting the creator behind this wonderful place. He is still working hard on maintaining his garden.

우리는 훌륭하고 평화로운 시간을 보냈습니다, 초대해 주셔서 감사합니다!

We traveled 2 hrs to get here and are glad we did. It’s such a beautiful garden, a large unique space. Must see when in Jeju. The cafe was amazing and even met the founder. Entry price was cheap for what you get. Even a chance to feed the koi inside the garden. Absolutely loved the experience. One of a kind place. Highly recommended. 10/10

Loved this garden and the philosophy behind the thought of the founder when he was curating the space. The trees were beautiful even in winter where there were little to no leaves. There’s a certain beauty to bare bonsai trees and there’s much to appreciate as well. There are signboards everywhere explaining how to appreciate the art of bonsai and how the principles of maintaining trees tie to the principles of life. I got to meet the owner and see him trim the bonsai trees, it was a treat!

However only the cafe is open, the restaurant was closed and there was a tea room that was closed which led to another part of the garden that was closed off.

This Bunjae (bonsai) garden was a balm for my soul.  The many amazing trees were just part of the sprawling garden with waterfalls that fell into pools full of the biggest koi. The staff were very friendly and there’s a coffee shop on site. Small meditations accompany the hundreds of trees. Make sure to read the story of the garden in the exhibition hall. I highly recommend making this stop if you’re travelling to Jeju and appreciate gardens of any kind.

My family had the pleasure of meeting the founder and director, Mr. Sung, as we toured the garden.

editorial_summary.overview: Deep inlet flanked by wooded cliffs, with a landmark bridge & pavilion famed for night views.

reviews.text: Nice suspension bridge and pavilion. Short walk from the car park and is pretty near Yongduam rock, but there’s nothing much to do other than just a quick snap of the photos.

great place, especially during outflow, one star less as currently the suspension bridge is under construction and it’s closed, so to cross the water you need to walk a little bit further south to the normal bridge
Beautiful place to see and probably one of my favorite photos!
The place is so lovely and peaceful. The water calms your mind and you can take your time in nature too. More than just worthy to visit. Literally loved it. 😊
A pleasant corner aping the narrow valley with the hanging bridge and a little park. A major local hangout point as well.

Geomun Oreum.adr_address: South Korea, 제주특별자치도 제주시 조천읍 선흘리

editorial_summary.overview: Self-guided & assisted tours are available at this ancient volcanic crater with trees & caves.

Geomun Oreum.formatted_address: South Korea, 제주특별자치도 제주시 조천읍 선흘리
Geomun Oreum.name: Geomun Oreum

reviews.text: As a Unesco natural heritage site there is nothing unusual in its outward appearance. However If you have a tour guide and understand korean, you'll realize why its called the mother of jeju. The trail is divided into three different courses that can take anywhere from 1-3 hrs.
This is only oreum (volcanic crater) that is a UNESCO World Heritage - it is quite underwhelming. It’s quite peaceful place. Entrance fee for what you see quite pricey
It's great to visit in Jeju. There are a lot of historical sites and nice scenery spots. This is Unesco. Must have place!
Took the shortest trail and already had calf pain the next day. The guide only speaks Korean and we returned without following the group which was good as we can walk more casually.
Take a deep breath within various plants and flower! Real healing, real health, good memory

Gimnyeong Maze Park.adr_address: 122 Manjanggul-gil, Gujwa-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do, South Korea

editorial_summary.overview: Leafy public park featuring a playground, ample green space & an elaborate topiary maze.

Gimnyeong Maze Park.formatted_address: 122 Manjanggul-gil, Gujwa-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do, South Korea
Gimnyeong Maze Park.name: Gimnyeong Maze Park

reviews.text:
A purr-fect spot for families and cat lovers alike! 🐱
The maze is a fun challenge for all ages, and the playground is a great place to unwind. Plus, enjoying delicious Jeju snacks like mandarine pizza while watching playful kittens is unbeatable.
Just be mindful of the cats' boundaries for a harmonious visit.

While the place has great potential, it could, in my opinion, benefit from some general maintenance to enhance the overall experience. 🛠️
For the rest, it's a nice way to spend a couple of hours with your kids, lover, or resident cats. 😉
Beautiful maze, with lots of playground for children , and a little gift when you're about to leave, it's only 7700won per adult for the entrance
Fun maze, challenging but not too much. Great feline friends and free cat treats!

Fun place to bring kids / dates to. With many cats to feed, and quite a number of things to do and play. Can spend easily about 2 hours here. Really impressed with the tripods around for you to take photos
This is very fun and took us more than 2 hours. Kids do not want to go back and want to come back again.

Jeolmul Natural Recreation Forest.adr_address: 584 Myeongnim-ro, Cheju, Jeju-do 63313, South Korea

editorial_summary.overview: Tranquil park featuring cedar-forest hiking trails, a volcanic hill, picnic tables & playgrounds.

Jeolmul Natural Recreation Forest.name: Jeolmul Natural Recreation Forest

reviews.text: Good forest park with nice trails to do. The forest is quite dense and the trails are well made for beginners, mid and extreme bike lovers. I did the Neonadri-gil trail which is about 3km and took about 90-100 minutes. Carry mosquito repellant
Very nice for strolling and resting in the forest, have a nice small hike to Jeonmul oreum for 1k won . Nice place to chill for hot afternoon, really cooling and quiet.
Really loved this place! Peaceful and quiet walk on wooden platforms and many tall trees surrounding you. Highly recommended if you love nature!
Even though it was raining and there was low cloud we were very impressed with the park. I wish we could visit again when the weather is better. All the tracks are well maintained.

This place is magical. It looks absolutely amazing I want to give it 6 stars. I very much recommend visit it and you won’t see anything like this ever because the climate in Jeju island itself is very different from anywhere in Korea. The trees in the forest are growing in an absolutely beautiful almost symmetrical manner and this forest is known for having healing energy. Definitely great to visit and have a small meditation session over there. ❤️

Hallim Park.adr_address: 300 Hallim-ro, Hallim-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do 63011, South Korea

editorial_summary.overview: Popular destination with a variety of scenic gardens, two caves & a small zoo, plus a folk village.

Hallim Park.formatted_address: 300 Hallim-ro, Hallim-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do, South Korea
Hallim Park.name: Hallim Park

reviews.text: Nice park with a couple of caves and a folk village. Also has a stone and bonsai section inside. Can cover the whole park in 90 minutes. Well maintained. Entrance is 15,000 Won

IMHO, the ticket price is super worth its while, as the place is humongous. As the main lava tubes is closed for renovations till 2025, Hallim park’s two caves are the only ones that are open and easily accessible by visitors. The caves are very beautiful and well maintained, and had mini stories (mother sculpture, the pillar of wisdom, etc). Besides the caves, there’s also a vast garden containing cacti species, bonsai etc and even a traditional folk house set up (so you can skip the folk village visit !!) in the premises.

Chose this place because it was close to our accommodation and my elderly mother loves gardens. What I thought was going to be a quick stroll through an arboretum ended up being  a 3.5 hour walk through the most gorgeous gardens, trees, and water and stone features. The small folk village and the 2 caves were an exciting bonus as well! I highly recommend a visit to Hallim Park. You will not be disappointed.

A great park with lots of different areas and plants to look at, the highlight were the two lava tube caves you could walk through. The only letdown were the enclosures the animals are kept in, the lack of space and environmental enrichment is disappointing.
Worth paying a visit! I like the cave most, which has natural air conditioning. Wide variety of plants and animals

Nuwemaru Street (Pedestrian Shopping Str.adr_address: Yeondong 7-gil, 연동 Jeju-si, Jeju-do 63123, South Korea
Nuwemaru Street (Pedestrian Shopping Str.formatted_address: Yeondong 7-gil, 연동 Jeju-si, Jeju-do, South Korea
Nuwemaru Street (Pedestrian Shopping Str.name: Nuwemaru Street (Pedestrian Shopping Street)

reviews.text: Don’t know if we went there on weekday afternoon/ evening around 4-5pm, so not much shops and restaurants had opened. And most of the shops are closed down. A good place for food, but not for shopping.

Dongmun Market Jeju is a place worth visiting. You can inherit the local culture and their daily life routine here. This market is divided into two - the fish market and the traditional market. Don't be alarm if you check Google Map and it's separate be a use its not! The traditional market is INSIDE the fish market. So enter the fish market regardless what Google Map is showing you...and you'll get there without wasting time figuring out!

Local delicacies and souvenirs are in the traditional market area. Apparently Jeju people don't eat Hoeteok because 4 days here and I never found one haha!
Worth checking out but a bit dainty and covers a couple blocks. Restaurants line the streets as well as global retailers so it is enjoyable to look at as you walk past it
Nice street, lots of tourists came here for shopping. Especially there are lots of Chinese.
Fun, cute little shops & street

Dodubong Peak.adr_address: South Korea, Jeju-do, Cheju, 도두동 산1
Dodubong Peak.formatted_address: South Korea, Jeju-do, Cheju, 도두동 산1
Dodubong Peak.name: Dodubong Peak

reviews.text: It is called 道頭峰 in Chinese. The road is nice and safe. I visited on Saturday and it is not crowded at all. The weather was perfect and the view was nice.
Nice small peak in north of Jeju. Short climb to the peak and nice 360 degree views from the top.

Simple climb up, nice surrounding views
Only one early cherry blossom bloomer surrounded by budding trees 🥲
Great spot for plane spotting at Jeju Airport, Jeju city and the sea
Excellent viewpoint to the airport, sea and Hallasan.

Jeju Light Garden.adr_address: 2346 Pyeonghwa-ro, Aewol-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do 63066, South Korea
Jeju Light Garden.formatted_address: 2346 Pyeonghwa-ro, Aewol-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do, South Korea
Jeju Light Garden.name: Jeju Light Garden

reviews.text:
This is a hidden gem in Jeju Island! Definitely make your way here if you can spare about an hour or so. After a long touristy day, Jeju Light Garden, was one of the places that was still open late! When we arrived, we were greeted by a nice gentleman who immediately wanted to take photos for us…my husband was like…nahhh uhh but he had no choice hahaha

It was a Tuesday night, and there were maybe 2-3 other couples…basically empty! So it was nice to have the garden all to ourselves. It’s a small place where you can explore within 40 mins and there’s also an inside section where there are props, photo booths, and arcade to be entertained with.

At the end, you’re allowed to choose only 1 photo for them to print for free! Loved it! Highly recommend for a short night visit.

Connect with me if you want to see more travel and food content! --> YouTube and IG RoseAndWorld7 ♡

Really happy with our experience at the Jeju Light Garden ✨️ We were greeted by a very friendly gentleman who took lots of pictures and videos for us. He really made the night feel so fun and special! Thank you for the precious memories ^^

They also have an indoor arcade & gift shop area where they will print a photo of your choice (upload via QR code)
It's a beautiful place. You can get 1 free photo print. 📸

A bit far to travel, can really get a cab if you go out of the place. We seek help from the staff there to get us a cab. But the lightings are amazing! Very adorable! Recommend to book it from klook to get a lower price entry.
Amazing place especially for kids, lots of activities. The light garden is superb, kids can enjoy lighting firecrackers as well

Manjanggul Lava Tube.adr_address: 182 Manjanggul-gil, Gujwa-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do 63348, South Korea

editorial_summary.overview: Long lava tube with unique formations, including stalactites & stalagmites, plus bats & insects.

Manjanggul Lava Tube.formatted_address: 182 Manjanggul-gil, Gujwa-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do, South Korea
Manjanggul Lava Tube.name: Manjanggul Lava Tube

reviews.text:
Can absolutely feel the wonder of nature and immerse yourself in it. Well preserved and easy to reach, the cave is a great place to visit!

Though only 1km is opened for public, you can find many different forms of igneous rock here and the whole atmosphere is so good here! (We spent around 1 hour to finish the whole journey and back to the entrance)

Apart from the cave, there is an indoor information center to learn the history of this place. Next to the center is a local restaurant offering fried cheese pork cutlet and udon. Recommend to give it a try also : )

Ticket price: 4,000 won per adult

Plenty of outdoor parking space is available.

The food in the restaurant at the entrance is amazing!  The host was very kind.  So, we had a great start to our visit.

The lava tube is stunning!  Not much more to say, but that it is a must see.

Walking will be challenging for those who struggle to walk on uneven surfaces - the floor is rough lava flow rock.  Would go here to reflect, cool off, or just marvel at the wonder of it.

Highly recommend.
It's a beautiful place to walk. Do ensure you have a good pair of walking shoes as the ground is slippery and uneven. You will probably need around 1 hour to walk to the end and back.

good place to visit and learn about geology.
quite easy to walk inside the cave.
temperature inside was cool. recommend to wear the suitable shoes for walking.
ticket is 4000 krw in case of individual.
bus is available, pls confirm before come.
it takes about30 mins to walk inside.

Interesting Lava Tube. It can be quite cold so wear a light jacket helps. Not a tough journey through the cave, my 6yo walk with a breeze. A bit wet and slippery so a good pair of hiking shoe helps. Enjoy!

Hallasan National Park.adr_address: South Korea, 63077, Jeju-do, Cheju, 특별자치도, 1100로 2070-61

editorial_summary.overview: National park with a large mountain, featuring many alpine plants, hiking trails & sweeping views.

Hallasan National Park.name: Hallasan National Park

reviews.text: Very difficult climb. I took a few breaks but not counting those (maybe 30 minutes total) it took just over three hours going up. There are a LOT of stairs!  Whereas in the U.S., it seems that switchbacks are more common, here at Hallasan at least, the choice is to simply go straight up the slope with stairs. In any case it is a very beautiful hike. I sprained a medial knee muscle on the right so it took a little longer going down. There are 2 restrooms. No water.

Fantastic views. 1100m of going up over 9km, evenly spread. Quite demanding as you need some good endurance. Beautiful surrounding and very rewarding path. With good weather, you can see the whole Jeju island.

What a beast of a mountain with a fair mix of stairs and rocks to hike over. Fairly shaded trail with lots of opportunity for wildlife encounter. Lots of cool rocks and platforms to nap on at the peak as well!

Amazing and decently tiring hike almost 2000m up, I made my ascent up at 10:10am and made it to the summit entrance gate at 12pm half an hour before it closed then another hour to get to the summit from there.

Definitely recommend going before 10am so you don’t have to rush up like I did.

Summit was awesome and make sure to bring some food so you can enjoy the views to a meal.
Made it back down in about 2 hours and saw a lot of deers on the way which was nice.
Legs were dead for about 4 days after so I’d recommend you plan a rest day or 2 after which I should’ve done.

Eoseungsaengak Trail - This was supposed to be a 30 minute hike to the top - umm nope - it was nothing but steps all the way up! Coming down was much quicker. Expect this hike to be at least an hour unless you are sprinting up to the top. This views were amazing and the hike was enjoyable. I did take little breaks to rest on the way up. It is a lot of steps!

Geomeun Oreum.adr_address: South Korea, Jeju-do, Cheju, 연동 산110-1
Geomeun Oreum.formatted_address: South Korea, Jeju-do, Cheju, 연동 산110-1
Geomeun Oreum.name: Geomeun Oreum

reviews.text: Accessibility and convenience are not good as there are no parking lots, bus stops, restrooms, or shopping malls nearby. (Visited in August 2019) The view is open toward New Jeju and is also good toward Hallasan Mountain. There is a private property nearby that prohibits entry, so be careful when visiting. It is not recommended to visit for sightseeing purposes.

When I first entered, I thought it was very gloomy because it was dark with a damp smell because it was the day after the rain (the road was narrow and there were too many tombs around when I went there), but on the way up, I really liked the phytoncide + the view from the top.
I couldn't see Mt. Halla properly because of the fog, but it was nice because the weather was neither hot nor cold.
I'm scared when I go alone because there's no one around.
**It was the day after it rained and the downhill slope was slippery so I skipped it once.

The access road was blocked due to heavy rain, and the road on the other side was not maintained, so there were many places where the road was not visible. The summit was not maintained, and the downhill road on the other side was too forested, so I got lost. I hope a poor person like me doesn't go alone... I'm a little proud, so I'll come back when the weather gets better.
Black Oreum was a very beautiful place. It was even better that the guide provided explanations. It is a place worth visiting at least once.

The road to Black Oreum
I liked it because it felt like a trail.

I went wearing Vans
It was slippery when going down.

On the way to the top
The ramp is quite high.

Take care :)

clean .
funny .

There was guide paint on the floor, so it was nice and comfortable to walk along, but it still seems a bit lacking to be called a mural alley.
The alley is still unfinished, but I think it will become a decent alley after a while.

Gwangot.adr_address: 777-1 Sinheung-ri, Jocheon-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do, South Korea
Gwangot.formatted_address: 777-1 Sinheung-ri, Jocheon-eup, Cheju, Jeju-do, South Korea
Gwangot.name: Gwangot

reviews.text: Walk along the coast and experience the original local atmosphere.

When you think of eastern Jeju, it's easy to think of sunrise, but there is a place where you can enjoy the beautiful sunrise in the eastern Jeju sea. It is Gwangot, and there is a beautiful sunset on the quiet coast. Dolphin spots that are sometimes found on the west coast can also be found here. It is also a dolphin spot that tourists are not aware of.

This is the best view among Jeju Ollae Road.
In particular, you can feel the comfort and refreshing atmosphere that can be found during a morning jog.
Especially near the white lighthouse, the entire 360° area is a photo zone.
I have no doubt that once you visit, you will fall in love with it.
Also, these days, the red sunset unfolds around 5 p.m., and this is the kind of place where you can enjoy the wonderful sight you only see in photos, along with the sea breeze and the smell of the sea, in real life, not in photos.
Don't just look at the beach during the holiday season, but don't miss out on the famous scenes that can be seen nearby in the morning and evening.

A stunning natural formation located on the wonderful and mysterious volcanic island of Jeju. After descending from the central volcano, we taxied through the soft and idyllic Jeju countryside to this UNESCO park. The tickets were incredibly cheap and we were fortunate enough to claim the last ones of the day. The underground tube plunges quick into the Earth. The stairs you start out on soon end, and the decline levels off into a flat, wet, and cold surface of black basalt. Within the Earth is an amazing place to be. The artificial lights are spectral, shining in pools of water gathered in the wrinkles of the hardened lava floor. There's very little to complain about here and the sights are unforgettable. A trip to Jeju is not complete without a descent through this prehistoric tube into the Earth. 5/5. Would descend again.
It was way cool to be where an actual volcano had erupted long ago.

Lotus Pond
Hagari, Aewol-eup, Jeju-si, is the largest pond in Jeju.
The area is about 10,000㎡ (3,000 pyeong). In the past, lotus flowers were in full bloom and the view was spectacular in the summer.
Due to the carelessness of some people nearby, the lotus flower was destroyed, making it impossible to see its beautiful appearance.
There are lotus flowers left in the small pond near the entrance.

The inside of the pond appears to be a green algae phenomenon, with a green tea latte appearance and dead carp floating on the water.

The banner said, "Please note that the lotus stems have been destroyed due to the release of green turtles by seniors, preventing lotus flowers from growing. Therefore, you will not be able to see lotus flowers until the extermination of green turtles is completed."
June 2022. Hagari Office

There is a legend behind the creation of the pond here...
During the reign of King Chungnyeol of the Goryeo Dynasty, the pond was the site of a bandit's home, where they built a large tile-roofed house and plundered passers-by. One day, a plot was hatched to attack the new judge's traveling party. An old man named Ttukhalmang, who lived in the village, informed the government of this fact and the bandits were eradicated. At this time, when the old man Ttukhalmang died, the government recognized the old woman's loyalty. It is said that in honor of him, he was given a government post and made to be revered as a deity of Jeju Hyanggyo.
After this, they tore down the tile-roofed houses where the bandits lived and dug a pond to catch rainwater for washing clothes and to use it as a watering pond for cows and horses.

Through extensive repair work in the 17th century, the pond with edible smoke was built for drinking water, the large pond for watering cows and washing, and the sink for washing vegetables.
In 1966, Yeonhwa Pond was designated as a fishing spot on Jeju Island and operated until the 1990s.

It is not known exactly when the lotus was planted in the pond, but it is said that in the mid-19th century, Jeju pastor Han Eung-ho made alcohol with lotus petals, drank it, recited poetry, and had his adoptive mother take care of the lotus during his inspection.
Additionally, in the history of the pond built in the village, it is recorded that lotus flowers were planted by the ‘Jaebusan Haga Community Association’ in 1949 when the embankment construction was in progress.

It is a rare place in Jeju Island where you can see lotus flowers, but unfortunately, it is now in ruins due to the extermination of green turtles. I hope that it will be restored to its original state as soon as possible.

Stressed rodents not being able to sleep and in full panic mode, a skink looking more dead than alive in a tiny box with dirty water, 2 monkeys in the saddest space you can imagine, and all the animals in small spaces or on a leash bot being able to move freely. I’m sure some of the caregivers love the animals but this should be stopped. Baby alpacas shouldn’t be dressed up in motorbike jackets for the photo and be refused to perform their natural behavior. reviews.text:
The Eorimok Valley Trail on Hallasan, Jeju Island, South Korea, is a captivating journey through diverse landscapes, offering a more accessible yet rewarding hiking experience. Spanning approximately 3.7 kilometers, this trail on the northern side of Hallasan provides a shorter route compared to other paths, making it an ideal choice for those seeking a more leisurely hike.

Eorimok Trail commences amidst lush forests, enveloping hikers in a serene atmosphere with the soothing sounds of nature. As the trail progresses, it gradually ascends, revealing panoramic views of Jeju's volcanic terrain. The relatively gentle incline makes it suitable for a wide range of hikers, including families and those looking for a less strenuous outdoor adventure.

One of the trail's highlights is Eorimok, a scenic rest area nestled along the way. Hikers can pause here to absorb the breathtaking surroundings and enjoy a moment of tranquility before continuing their ascent. The varied flora, including vibrant wildflowers, adds to the trail's aesthetic appeal.

Eorimok Valley Trail provides a perfect balance of accessibility and natural beauty, making it an excellent choice for those who wish to explore Hallasan's splendor without undertaking an overly challenging hike. The trail offers a delightful escape into Jeju's pristine landscapes, creating lasting memories for nature enthusiasts of all ages.

Jeongbang Waterfall is one of the most famous waterfalls in Seogwipo, located on Jeju Island, South Korea. It is unique because it's one of the few waterfalls in Asia that falls directly into the ocean. The waterfall is about 23 meters high, and visitors can enjoy the scenic beauty of the water cascading over cliffs into the sea.

To reach the waterfall, there is a short, easy hike down a series of steps. The area surrounding the waterfall has large boulders, so visitors should wear comfortable shoes to navigate the rocky terrain safely.

The entrance fee is approximately 2,000-3,000 KRW for adults. There are public restrooms and small shops selling drinks and snacks near the entrance.

It's recommended to visit during the early morning or late afternoon to avoid large crowds, especially during peak tourist seasons. The waterfall may also look more impressive after rainfall, as the water flow tends to be stronger.

Be mindful of weather conditions, as the area around the falls can become slippery when wet. Additionally, swimming is not allowed, but you can get quite close to the falls for photos.

A cultural village that preserves the traditional lifestyle and culture of Jeju Island, showcasing the architecture, customs, and daily life of its people during the 19th century. The village consists of around 100 traditional houses and structures, including thatched-roof homes, ancient government offices, shrines, and schools.

Visitors can explore different areas that reflect Jeju’s agricultural, fishing, and mountain village life. The village offers insight into local traditions, including the distinctive Jeju dialect, unique agricultural tools, and the island’s matriarchal society, exemplified by the female divers known as "haenyeo."

For those planning to visit, the village is open year-round and offers various cultural performances and seasonal events. It’s a great spot to learn about Jeju’s history and heritage, and there are also opportunities to try traditional crafts and experience local food.

It’s advisable to wear comfortable walking shoes, as the village is spread out, and be prepared for variable weather conditions, especially during summer and winter months. Keep in mind that most signage and descriptions are available in both Korean and English, but guided tours are also offered if you want a more detailed experience.

Lastly, it can get busy during peak tourist seasons, so visiting during weekdays or off-peak times may make for a more relaxed experience.

Jusangjeolli Cliff is a natural wonder located on the southern coast of Jeju Island, South Korea.

It features striking hexagonal basalt columns formed by the rapid cooling of lava as it came into contact with the ocean. The cliffs stand tall, creating a dramatic contrast with the turquoise sea.

If you're planning to visit, here are a few things to keep in mind:

Jusangjeolli is located in the Jungmun area, near Seogwipo, making it easily accessible from popular tourist spots like the Jungmun Tourist Complex.

There's an entrance fee to access the viewing platform, which offers a spectacular view of the cliffs and the ocean. The best time to visit is during high tide when the waves crash against the rocks, creating a stunning visual display.

There is a well-maintained walking path around the cliffs, offering different angles and vantage points for photos. The area is family-friendly and accessible for most visitors. However, be mindful of weather conditions, as it can be slippery on rainy or windy days.

Nearby attractions include Cheonjeyeon Waterfalls, Yeomiji Botanical Garden, and the International Convention Center. You can easily make a day of exploring the surrounding areas.

Seongeup Folk Village, or 성읍민속마을, nestled on Jeju Island, is a living testament to Korea's cultural heritage. The village seamlessly merges history with contemporary life, preserving traditional thatched-roof homes, called hanoks, and showcasing the island's distinctive lifestyle. Strolling through the narrow lanes feels like a journey back in time, with locals engaging in traditional crafts. The village's historical landmarks, like the fortress walls and ancient shrines, add a layer of historical richness. Despite its tourist popularity, the authenticity of Seongeup Folk Village endures, offering a genuine glimpse into Jeju's past. Visitors can savor cultural performances and culinary delights, making it a comprehensive and enriching cultural experience.

rudded rock formations, sesonal effected flow Waterfall, walking trails and rest area

reviews.text: Someone said it’s a perfect spot for a rainy day in Jeju, but it’s wrong!!! Don’t get me wrong, the glasshouse garden was big, impressive and pretty, but the outside garden was prettier. And on the rainy day, you can’t see Hallasan and the views…. I think it will be great to pack lunch on a sunny day and enjoy the beautiful garden all day.
This is one of the best botanical gardens we've been to! Lots of plants to see, lots of spots to make good photos. Definitely recommended if you are in Jeju
I enjoyed my visit. The outside gardens could have more to offer.

Not worth paying KRW 12,000 per person to visit this botanical garden. The garden is unkept and poorly managed - other than a few patches of flowers and lawn.  The ponds have bad stench and even seen rubbish in the bushes.

You may be better parking your car there and walk down to Cheonjiyeon waterfall by crossing the Seonim bridge.
Great place to visit, you can climb to the top of the tower for a great view. Loved the floral fragrances inside.

Experience the man made wonders of the world and other famous architectural wonders from across the countries in a scaled down version.
One of the places which the kids will enjoy…..there is information provided about the structures in English as well, which is good.
The place also has an amazing cafe at the entrance and a convenience store. Also has a Korean buffet restaurant with ample free parking space.
The souvenir shop at the exit is good offering a variety of options, from chocolate to decorative items to accessories.
The place is easy to locate on the map.

I recommend skipping it. Admission ticket is 7000 won per pax.

If u have time this also can be one among the places that you can visit. They have al the world wonders at one places.

It can be enjoyed by all the age group peoples.
it is always good to take a car and travel in jeju.

The train ride is exciting!
There are not many visitors though.
Ticket 12000 won per person.tge park very big more than I expected

Good spacious clean place with kind staff.

Not challenging enough for serious cart lovers.

But you can have your or your kid's first cart driving within relatively safe condition.

There are a maze to explore and a horse riding experience at the same site, which allows you to enjoy several events for kids in a short time.

The maze is not hard to pass through, so please  do not make a visit only for the adventure.
The place has this gokart tract. The location is close to the Jeju world cup stadion.

JITC. Come in spring and you can see beautiful cherry blossoms here.
A place to share and learn new things from people in Asia Pacific region. It's an amazing place that people should visit once in a lifetime
I really love and miss this place.
Good global training centre

reviews.text: Went Scuba diving. It was my first time in Korean waters and it is quite okay underwater despite the corals were damaged. The surface waves were strong so it was dangerous. What was more dangerous was the fishing boats that were inconsiderate of floating SMBs. The safety is not quite ensured yet compared to other countries' famous diving spots.
Crystal clear water with 10~15m depth
Went on submarine trip.... great views under water and went down to 45m. Missed somethings as commentary only in korean
Beautiful island
good
A quick walk over the bridge to the island that doesn’t take too long to walk around, there are lots of places to take photos.
Nice place for viewing sunset. A walk around the island took less than half an hour and is an easy walk.

we after dinner just nice hear music very happen ,Saeyeongyo Bridge here happy to watch music fountain.

all people come in day time, only us come in night time 😀😀😀

A boardwalk walking trail around the island that starts from Saeyeongyo Bridge. This course is easily completed under an hour. There are no entry fees.
The trail is well maintained. Views are great from the island. You can see Munseom Island from here.

Very very beautiful, lovely and tiny island with wonderful nature. It takez around up tp 15-20 mins to walk around , follow the trial and see everything on it but it is definitely truly majestic with its views and green areas! 😊

reviews.text: This was not worth the trip even if you’re here to see Jeongbang Waterfall (2,000 won). For adults the admission is 10,000 won and place smelled of mildew. It’s 3 floors with rooftop view which is pretty. Not sure I would recommend unless you’re a fan of this artist. Museums in area closed on Mondays. Recommend stopping by Droptop cafe next to museum for Hallabong ice blend drink on a hot day.
Artist Lee Wal Jong built the building and it houses his artwork. Love.
Most amazing part is level two, meditation 🧘‍♀️ room.
Beautiful waterfall and  art museum cafe must go.

Expensive and not much to see. All the paintings were the same... flowers, golf, couples having sex or watching TV. It is nice for a gallery of an artist and also for his workshop. But felt like I wasted my time and money... spent 30 minutes there.

reviews.text: The place was dead so we didn't have to wait in line.  They have 3 rides that seemed pretty cool.  Overall it is a small park with not a lot going on but because we didn't have to share or stand in line it made it better.
If you have a child less than 100cm tall, you are limited to just 4 rides and price is quite expensive if you visit with a child and can't enjoy a lot of rides with them.

The park is a burst of vibrant colors, instantly igniting a lively and exciting atmosphere upon entry. Although there aren't many thrilling rides, the short queues are a definite plus, allowing you to enjoy the rides repeatedly. It's an excellent choice for families with kids, providing a joyful experience. Don't forget to purchase your tickets online in advance for potential discounts.

It was such an underrated place! We thoroughly enjoyed ourselves. The place is well kept. The rides were awesome and thrilling enough. My kids are 9 and 11.
The price is unbeatable. We enjoyed the food there too. Overall, it was a very enjoyable day at the theme park.

- singapore tourists

Small and simple play ground near mall and resort. Several riding located in there. The riding level is adapted to children fr 7year to 12year. This theme park adapted to family. You can walk around about 30min just watching. This park not include water park.

reviews.text:
A bit disappointed on the street foods, not delicious and price is quite high: there is a row of chairs in the middle for you to consume the foods but no table.

Some chairs are with the food stain and left over foods.. look dirty and uncomfortable.

The market skill is not really big.. many stalls selling oranges 🍊 and there are many samples to try before you buy. However, they don't look friendly may be the language barrier.

There is a covered multi storey carpark next to the market if you are driving.

We took less than 20mins  to walk the whole market and 20mins to try some foods.

A nice place enjoyed walking around. So much things to see n try. Jeju tangerine 🍊 really nice. Since it is crowded i usually hold my daughter hand n just video the place. Love the culture over here.

Need to come here with a empty stomach. 😕 sadly i came here after tea break. So much food i cant eat. Wrong timing.

A great market for street food and snacks.
We tried food from various stalls and they were all great.
The standout is the honey and peanut buns, but the stuffed peppers and savoury egg buns were also good.
Lots of Jeju products can also be bought here and we tried the orange juice.

Nice place to walk around with many food and souvenirs stores around, pretty crowded too.

Parking around this place is challenging but I found a multi story carpark nearby (see my screenshot) and had even free parking. Make sure to pay for the parking if needed at the self payment machine as you can check whether you need to pay or not.

I loved this place. Fresh seafood, black pork, fruit and vegetables for sale to take home and cook. Or you can hit up the food stalls for street food if you want to eat there. Great place for shopping for gifts to take home from Jeju Island.
Good place for fishing~
Sleepy port town in Jeju. Beautiful ocean views without too many people or cars. Great place to get away for a while.
Slight cold day when I visited in March
Scuab diving boats leave here for Beom-seom island. Small but convenient, close to the nice diving points.

Many scuba diver go dive from here
Dive spot 'bum island' near

reviews.text: A good place to unwind. If you love plants and flowers, this is a good place to visit. They also have cafes so you can really sit down and soak in the nature.

Late review but came last December'23 when there was a snow storm that covered the garden beautifully. It was definitely cold as hell but we were rewarded with beautiful scenery and lovely pictures taken around the huge garden.

It was a huge place to wander around, one of the places to go to in Jeju Island, South Korea especially in Springtime. A lot of hydrangeas in bloom when we went there. My favorite area was the herb garden. Lovely!

We were here in the end of April and were a bit disappointed that we did not see more flowers. It is more of a tourist place with photo opportunities than a botanical garden for the sake of plants and flowers. So for us who are interested in the botany of Jeju, it was a bit of a disappointment. Having said all that - still a nice place.

The camellias were out of season, but the garden full of hydrangeas was beautiful, and the small lake, the path between the trees, the observatory, and the walking path were all pleasing to the eyes and a joy to walk around.

Hueree Nature Life Park.adr_address: 256 Sillyedong-ro, Namwon-eup, Seogwipo, Jeju-do 63608, South Korea

editorial_summary.overview: Scenic, serene park with many flowers & plants, plus pony rides & small animals, such as pigs.

reviews.text: I recently visited Hueree Natural Life Park and had a wonderful time! The park is beautifully maintained with a wide variety of flora and fauna, offering a peaceful escape into nature. The walking trails are scenic and well-marked, making it easy to explore the lush surroundings. The highlight for me was the vibrant hydrangea garden, which was in full bloom. The green plum juice from the cafe is refreshing and delicious. The staff was friendly and knowledgeable, providing interesting information about the park's natural features. Overall, it's a fantastic destination for nature lovers and families looking to spend a relaxing day outdoors. Highly recommend!

We visited it in mid-September. the famous pink flowers are ridiculous and only appear pink with the maximum saturation of the phone. Many areas rich in flowers have half of them dried, what a fantastic experience

Beautiful blooms by season, hydrangeas for us during end May. However other than that it’s abit of a snooze fest. Bring your mothers and aunties though they will definitely love the place for photos. There’s also animal corner which is kind of sad…..
Hydrangeas are in full bloom now, if you come early at 9am, you can skip the crowd and see the flowers all for yourself. Please come soon before the Hydrangeas season is over.

There are many entertainments in the park. We went in Autumn and managed to see muhly pink grass and hydrangea flowers. There are black pig shows which they would release the pigs and carrots can be bought to feed them. Tickets can also be bought for orange picking experience. Apart from that, there are also many photo taking opportunities. Good for family with kids.

reviews.text: This was awesome! Especially worth it after 6pm when they turn the lights on as for us it made it more special and gave us more photo opportunities. They have a lot of different sections that you can explore and walk around in.

Nice garden, mostly the attraction are the lights which are beautiful at night. You will only visit this place if you want to do photoshoots or photo op for ig or social media. It would not be in my priority lists to visit.
Lighting in the evening so you can come there just before sunset to experience the day and night looks. Tickets are abit expensive but nice place still

The place was really beautiful both in the morning and night! When we reached at around 5 plus pm, we were told that there will be free foot spa for us and that foot spa was very comfortable. It was a good stress reliever and it also helps with muscle cramps. If you come after 6pm i think you will need to pay 12,000 won. But it will be good to check if the free spa is still applicable. 10/10 would recommend people to come.

Come in the day to take pictures of flowers and night for the lights.
Very nice garden. Very nice details and views. The garden is well maintained, but the props could do with a lick of paint. We had a pleasant visit. A must see when you like gardens.

reviews.text:
Great place. So many visitors.^_^ sadly my ankle doesnt allow me to climb much after temple climb... n my daughter the whiner.. 😆

Came at right time no fog great weather n unbelievable beautiful blue sky. My wife enjoyed the top view with my son.

Its hot but the breeze cools everthing. 😎

It’s the symbol of Jeju island. You won’t be disappointed!! Go up and see the beautiful volcanic rocks and the geological wonders.
And don’t forget there is free area as well, which has great views toward the summit, also a tiny temple as well.
For Korean people, there is a culture and nature guide (not sure if they can speak English) on the top and can give us good and interesting information about the summit, Jeju culture, nature and amazing stories.
The climb up was not that bad, and the going down was easier. There were lots of resting places along the way as well. Lovely vantage points.
Not too difficult to climb up with steps, coming down was easy with better stairs than on the way up

Worth the hike! Breathtaking views along the way!

A heritage and wonder of nature indeed! ✨

Must visit!

Is a very big park suitable for slow walk, running man fans should come too

Cave, gardens, and even a field of orange trees! Pretty cool and zen.

We have been there with our three years old daughter. The zoo for some reason was closed. Next, they have not allowed for our child even to  pet a horse, if for example my wife would pay for a ride. Finally, we found much better and pleasant places on the island.

Not understanding the language didn't stop us from enjoying the show.

The acrobatic moves of the performers on the horses were a sight to behold.

Our child definitely enjoyed herself just watching the horses and performers.

I went horse riding with my husband and my mom. It was the most bizarre experience we had. I felt like we paid to watch the horses get beaten up. Horse riding here allows kids on the big horse instead of only ponies else where. Kids were thrilled!

Ice cream good

reviews.text: Picture perfect park on the water. There are bike and electric scooter rentals for those who are looking for more than a walk. There are cafes nearby with great views too. We spent several hours here on a hot day enjoying the cool breeze.

Very nice place to stop and take a walk and take photos, on windy days beware, the wind can be quite strong, certain part of the path can closed due to high tide.

Went during spring and the path after the lighthouse was closed off due to high tides, if you want to walk the entire path check the weather and tide schedules.

At the start of the coastal road there is a mango juice store, nice place to rest and drink some mango juice.

It was pretty interesting to see the windmills up close and personal. A must see when coming to jeju.
Very peaceful place and nice to take a stroll to see the gigantic blades of the windmill at work. (When in operation, the windmill makes a whooshing sound and is quite therapeutic to hear, lol!)
Beautiful coastal walk, catch nice views of the windmills and sea, there’s toilet near the carpark area, easy stroll with a nice weather
What a great experience seeing wind turbines close up. It would be a nice place to have a picnic in more warmer sunnier weather.

reviews.text: The uphill climb is not something that is easy to see. I set off to go up the Saryeoni Forest Trail, but the mountain was steeper than I expected. I don't think I made it even halfway, but my t-shirt was soaked with sweat, so it looks like I did quite a bit of exercise. There are a lot of trees, so the view from up to the observatory is a bit limited, but you can see other nearby oreums very well. It was nice to go all the way up, but I wonder when I'll come down again, so I'll have to choose a flat trail carefully next time.

This is an oreum located within Jeolmul Natural Recreation Forest. Because I stayed at a forest house in a natural recreation forest, I was able to climb Jeolmul Oreum early in the morning.

It took about 20 to 30 minutes to get inside Jeolmul Natural Recreation Forest and from the beginning of the oreum to the first observatory. (one way)

It was a cloudy day, but the clear air and morning energy made it the most wonderful moment of all the Jeju Oreums I have ever been to.

There are many beautiful scenery inside Jeolmul Natural Recreation Forest, such as cedar road and pine forest road, but I also recommend climbing the Oreum.
The air is nice and it’s nice to take a walk with my family.

Photo taken in mid-December 2022
From the entrance to Jeolmul Oreum (wooden pillar) with a 7-year-old girl
It took about 40 minutes to reach the summit.
The path up was well-maintained and not difficult.
The trail from the top to the top took about 15 minutes.

Is the climb a little out of breath?
The road is more slippery than I thought.
I think you should be careful if it rained a little the day before.
The observatory is located along the ridge, so it’s very easy.
Just a little bit of climbing? Haha
Anyway, the scenery is refreshing.
I felt like I was inside the clouds because there were a lot of clouds, but this observatory made me feel close to the sky.
I think it would be much prettier on a clear day.
It is better to go in through the entrance and come out through the entrance.
They say it takes several hours to go to the Jangsaeng Forest Trail.

editorial_summary.overview: Exhibits about green tea, an observatory with countryside views & a popular gift shop & cafe.

Osulloc Tea Museum.formatted_address: 15 Sinhwayeoksa-ro, Andeok-myeon, 특별자치도, Seogwipo, Jeju-do, South Korea

reviews.text: Not sure if I'd call this a museum. It's a really nice cafe with a shop inside it and fields surrounding it. Nevertheless, going and trying some of their tea desserts, coupled with the aesthetics of the environment was a fun and worthwhile experience. We also got some really well decorated souvenirs.

If you're a tea lover, this experience will be awesome. I did find the place a bit busy on a Friday afternoon, maybe too busy and full of tourist. The tea wasn't mind blowingly good, but was refreshing to a taste and have a sample. The place seems small for the size of people it can handle and the outside has its tea bushes you can see for miles. The cafe was packed with people and was hard to even grab a table or seat.

The staff was super friendly and helpful.
Nice cafe and tea plantation to visit in Jeju. We have been twice during our stay and it was always a bit crowded which is understandable as the tea and desserts were delicious.

Really fun place to visit which has a lot of products and of course a place to buy tea and tea products. There are several areas such as the cafe and then the buildings closer to the tea plantation which is where you can buy cosmetics and other tea leaf products.

Free museum that focuses on how tea is cherished and how it grows. There are samples to try and varieties you can buy. There are tea drinks you can enjoy there and desserts. Outside are scenic plots of tea fields, great for pictures. A must see when going to Jeju Island.

Jeju Museum of Contemporary Art.adr_address: 35 Jeoji 14-gil, Cheju, Jeju-do 63017, South Korea

editorial_summary.overview: Concrete contemporary art museum, offering an outdoor theater & kids' sculpture park.

Jeju Museum of Contemporary Art.name: Jeju Museum of Contemporary Art

reviews.text: This is a nice museum for modern art, many pieces focusing on local artist. Many pieces are also out in the garden so you will get a nice stroll. My fiancé and I had a great time visiting the Jeju world natural heritage centre and walking the trails. You first must book a reservation before going (you won’t receive a confirmation email, just a confirmation on the webpage). Once you arrive there is a check in space where you pay and get your ticket. You then go to sign up for the tour, I assume, we weren’t fully sure since none of the staff spoke English. Our time slot was at 9 am. Inside the natural heritage centre you can see exhibits, use the washroom and access wifi. We did this while we waited for the rest of the group. There were about 30 people on this tour, maybe more, people of all ages but everyone spoke Korean so we were a little left out. The tour guide was amazing, she kept a great walking/hiking pace and seemed to have a lot of knowledge (I wouldn’t know as it was entirely in Korean). My only complaint is that you must stay with the group, we thought we could maybe hike the course on our own, but it’s a large group and you can get caught behind some slow walkers. Also there is a decent amount of talking, so the 2 hour section we did about half hour of it I’d say was explanations and stopping to talk.
The trail itself is beautifully laid out, lots of steps/stairs and then carpeted trail and lovely look out points!
Enjoyable. We did the longest hike and took us about three hours. Make sure you book your ticket in advance
